  <mainDescription>&lt;h3>&#xD;
    Welcome to the Practices for Rational Requirements Composer!&#xD;
&lt;/h3>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    This configuration presents the IBM(R) Rational(R) framework for requirements definition and management, along with&#xD;
    guidance on how to use Rational Requirements Composer as part of this framework.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    &lt;img alt=&quot;Framework for requirements definition and management&quot; align=&quot;center&quot; src=&quot;./resources/framwork.jpg&quot; />&lt;br />&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;h3>&#xD;
    Introduction&#xD;
&lt;/h3>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    Written by Walker Royce, Vice President, IBM Software Services-Rational:&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;blockquote style=&quot;MARGIN-RIGHT: 0px&quot; dir=&quot;ltr&quot;>&#xD;
    &lt;p>&#xD;
        The industry has often blamed poor requirements as the number one reason for ineffective software delivery. The&#xD;
        industry is challenged with achieving better requirements. Why? Well, for two reasons. First, in my view,&#xD;
        requirements-probably the most misused word in our industry-rarely describe anything that is truly required. Nearly&#xD;
        everything is negotiable. Second, the difference between poor requirements and better requirements is&#xD;
        indistinguishable. There are not proven metrics for measuring such things. Consequently, there is a very weak basis&#xD;
        of best practices in requirements engineering. Organizations that get overly prescriptive in requirements process&#xD;
        tend to fail. From my experience, the #1 failure pattern in software development is to define a 5 digits of&#xD;
        precision version of the requirements when you only have a 1 digit of precision understanding of the real need.&#xD;
        This excess precision is usually driven by an overly rigorous requirements engineering process.&lt;br />&#xD;
        &lt;br />&#xD;
        Organizations that achieve better results are more honest about the uncertainty inherent early in the lifecycle and&#xD;
        tend to accept more agile techniques for scope definition such as:&lt;br />&#xD;
        1. The need for evolving requirements detail--NOT early frozen requirements.&lt;br />&#xD;
        2. Existing patterns/components/services affect the requirements decisions just as much as the requirements affect&#xD;
        the design decisions -- NOT requirements drive design.&lt;br />&#xD;
        &lt;br />&#xD;
        Consequently, requirements elicitation, composition, synthesis and management are much more of a lifecycle art and&#xD;
        not well served by a prescriptive engineering process. This places more burden on the collaborative, negotiating&#xD;
        skills across stakeholders, shared vision, and the need for iterative feedback from executable software&#xD;
        demonstrations. Such creative activities driven mostly by human collaboration are not well suited to detailed,&#xD;
        prescriptive processes. They are well suited to suggestive practices that capture techniques, guidance and measures&#xD;
        from successful patterns of success. These practices provide mature starting points for tailoring your plans and&#xD;
        activities.&lt;br />&#xD;
        &lt;br />&#xD;
        Requirements Composer provides a powerful collaborative platform. The practice configuration for Requirements&#xD;
        Composer provides active practice guidance to accelerate a team's effective proficiency and reuse of proven&#xD;
        patterns of success.&lt;br />&#xD;
    &lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;/blockquote>&#xD;
